english:
  title: Prayer to the Three Pure Ones
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Radiant are the Three Pure Ones,
    who deliver mankind from death's domain,
    who guide the soul through life's passage.

    A sincere heart flows with heaven's current—
    I offer my humble devotion,
    and dare to seek the ear of the Highest.

    In those late days of Hongwu's reign,
    in autumn of the year of the Dog and Tiger,
    when the dynasty trembled on the brink,
    when death pressed close upon all sides—
    through hidden grace I was spared the ruin,
    yet brought sorrow to my father's heart,
    carrying lifelong anguish in my breast.
    I weep blood, yet what can tears restore?

    I repent my sins and seek to renew myself,
    yet wonder if my ancestors' spirits
    might linger still in darkness,
    and whether my people lack true peace.

    How can one house flourish in blessing?
    How can all things be brought to harmony?
    These questions swirl within me,
    gathering in this small frame.

    I pray for grace from the Great Creator,
    that my humble wishes might be fulfilled.

    At the Hall of Radiant Illumination,
    we perform the solemn rites of blessing.
    With moat and rampart, we build our altar,
    offering spring and autumn prayers with care.
    Such are the ways of our kingdom's ritual,
    yet my heart still yearns for more.

    So I have built a small house in my dwelling,
    a place for worship and reverence,
    where I hang portraits of the sages.
    In the stillness of night,
    I feel them present at my left and right.
    Sweet incense rises in spirals—
    I stand before the divine with solemn heart.

    I do not merely seek blessings to come,
    but offer gratitude for mercies past.

    I humbly pray: let the Supreme Being show compassion,
    let the Holy Sages kindle their mercy.
    Look upon my accumulated sincerity,
    pity the anguish of my soul.

    May my departed father and mother
    be released from the sufferings of the underworld.
    May they ascend quickly to the abode of immortals,
    joining the true play of the celestials,
    dwelling forever in the Purple Palace.

    May all the souls of my ancestors
    receive the protection of the Highest,
    attaining the realm of perfect joy.

    May all creatures great and small find peace,
    and may my line flourish for a hundred generations,
    growing ever stronger through the ages.
  footnotes:
    - The Three Pure Ones (三淸) represent the highest deities in Daoism, embodying cosmic principles and spiritual truth.
    - The Hall of Radiant Illumination (昭格殿) refers to a sacred shrine for ancestor veneration and divine communication.
    - The reference to Hongwu's reign and the year of the Dog and Tiger suggests this was written during a period of political upheaval in the early Ming dynasty.
    - The imagery of the Purple Palace and the abode of immortals reflects Daoist concepts of the afterlife and celestial realms.
